<li>However , results summarized in Table 6 show that cells transformed with pU-T18C and pK-T25 derivatives encoding fusions of the T18 and T25 fragments to wild-type MelR score as Mal and contain signiﬁcantly increased levels of - galactosi-dase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The explanation for this is that MelR self-associates and brings together the T18 and T25 fragments to generate ade-nylate cyclase activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data in Table 3 show that MelR activity in vivo is not affected by the change Asn-222 - + Ala in helix-turn-helix 1 , but is halved by the change Ser-271 - + Ala in helix-turn-helix 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data in Table 3 show that the change Ser-272 - + Asn reduces MelR activity by 75 % , the change Arg-269 - .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>These are the first reported single amino acid changes in MeIR , and although their effects do not provide a direct proof that motif 2 is involved in DNA binding , they do raise the possibility that MelR differs from AraC , in which changes in the helix-turn-helix corresponding to motif 1 have clearer effects than changes in the sequence corresponding to motif 2 ( Brunelle & Schleif , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>To determine the relative levels of MelR protein , we estimated the amount of extract required to totally retard labelled EcoRIHindIll KK43 fragment in gel binding assays [ in these experiments , we used labelled fragments at concentrations higher than the estimated association constants in order to titrate MelR protein in the extracts independently of small differences in binding ; for protocols see Webster et al. ( 1989 ) and the Experimental section ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because MelR binds independently to the two binding sites in the KK33 fragnent , up to four retarded bands are observed , the intensities of which vary according to the MelR concentration ( Caswell et al. , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>Site 2 is filled at higher concentrations of MelR , resulting in a number of more retarded bands which are difficult to resolve ( Caswell et al. , 1992b ; and Figure 3a ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Crude extracts were made from M182 [ pAA207 ] , as described in MATERIALS AND METHODS , section b , and were used as a source of MelR ; control extracts were made from M182 [ pAA204 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>l , R-H , .2 , and R-H , .3 ) , are shown by arrows ( c ) Fusion of meiR to IaeZ and deletions in melR To prove that the footprints and band shifts we had observed were due to MelR binding , rather than some other component of the crude extracts from M182 [ pAA207 ] , we needed to purity MelR protein or , iteratively , to attach a ` tag ' to MelR in the crude extracts .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , MelR bound to DNA carrying Site 1 protects five sets of bases against hydroxyl radical digestion ; such protection would result from two MelR subunits bound side by side , penetrating four adjacent major grooves at the DNA target ( T. A. Belyaeva , unpublished results ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , some of the gene expressions are controlled by cAMP-CAP , such as malFG , malKM , lamB , melAB ( through MelR ) and glpF , suggesting that Era-dE overproduction affects the carbon source metabolism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12125819" target="_blank">12125819</a>]<br></li>
<li>All the MelR derivatives except MelR314 and MelR45 were clearly detected by autoradiography after SDS-PAGE and appeared to be the correct size .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Double-substituted MelR represses pmelR less efﬁciently , and repression by MelR carrying YD25 FY53 together with the NI183 FS191 or QR238 TA277 changes is minimal .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , when MelR carrying the YD25 , FY53 , NI183 , and FS191 substitutions is fused to the T18 and T25 fragments , cells score as Mal and contain low levels of - galactosidase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>With pJW15 encoding the YD25 , FY53 , KE123 , SF167 , KR182 , or NI183 MelR substitutions , only 0.2 to 0.5 M melibiose is required .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the combination of the YD25 , FY53 , NI183 , and FS191 substitutions converts MelR to its melibiose-triggered state , we conclude that the association between MelR subunits must differ according to their conformation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>- Galactosidase activity in WAM132 melR lac cells carrying KK43 or JK141 pmelAB : : lac fusions and pJW15a - Galactosidase activity MelR encoded by pJW15 derivative KK43-pRW50 JK141-pRW50 No With No With melibiose melibiose melibiose melibiose Wild type 23 1043 3 703 YD25 FY53 NI183 FS191 MT243 substitution , which appears to freeze MelR in its melibiose-free conformation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , MelR carrying the YD25 , FY53 , NI183 , and FS191 substitutions , as well as being able to activate pmelAB carried by the KK43 fragment , is also able to activate the JK141 promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the MelR proteins were produced in low amounts and are of similar molecular mass to other cell proteins and so could not be quantified .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Note that our results are most easily explained by supposing that MelR , like many AraC family members , is functional as a dimer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sequence accession numbers are : FeaR , EMBUGenBank X99402 ; XylS , SWISS-PROT P07859 ; RhaR , SWISS-PROT P09378 ; RhaS , SWISS-PROT P09377 ; AraC , SWISS-PROT P03021 ; MelR , SWISS-PROT P10411 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9043126" target="_blank">9043126</a>]<br></li>
<li>The displacement of a second repressing protein , NagC , could serve the equivalent function for ChbR as the occupation of a low afﬁnity site for AraC and MelR , i.e. allow ChbR to switch into activation mode .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15066032" target="_blank">15066032</a>]<br></li>
<li>The striking parallels between AraC and MelR led us to consider whether the light switch model applies to MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>From our study , we can conclude that , though the ligandfree forms of both E. coli AraC and MelR proteins strongly repress expression from their own promoters , different mechanisms are used for ligand-dependent switching to a state that can activate transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC/XylS family proteins whose DNA binding domains do not activate transcription well -- including MelR and ToxT ( Howard et al. , 2002 ; Prouty et al. , 2005 ) -- may be similar to RhaR and unable to effectively contact RNAP ( or otherwise activate transcription at a step after DNA binding ) in the absence of effector ( Fig. 6C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among proteins in this subset , including RhaS and RhaR as well as XylS , MelR , and UreR , this domain is generally required for dimerization and/or effector binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>This DNA-binding domain has also been shown to be involved in transcription activation in a number of AraC/XylS family proteins including Ada , RhaS , AraC , MelR , MarA , SoxS , XylS , and UreR ( 1 , 4 , 5 , 15 , 16 , 20 -- 22 , 37 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15342598" target="_blank">15342598</a>]<br></li>
<li>This inhibitory function of the NTD is not found in MelR and RhaS/RhaR ( 18 , 56 , 58 ) but is found in AraC and XylS ( 15 , 41 , 59 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24013633" target="_blank">24013633</a>]<br></li>
<li>This group includes AraC , RhaS , RhaR , and MelR from E. coli and XylS from Pseudomonas putida , which are among the most well characterized of the AraC/XylS family proteins ( 4 , 5 , 8 , 12 , 13 , 16 , 19 , 29 , 30 , 38 , 39 , 53 -- 55 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to advance our understanding of the AraC family , we have focussed on the E. coli melibiose operon , which is regulated by MelR , a close homologue of AraC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Examples of proteins that regulate carbon metabolism ( and the carbon source and species they are found in ) are AraC ( L-arabinose , Escherichia coli ) , RhaS and RhaR ( L-rhamnose , E. coli ) , XylS ( benzoates , Pseudomonas putida ) , and MelR ( melibiose , E. coli ) ( 2 , 14 , 33 , 36 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10464186" target="_blank">10464186</a>]<br></li>
<li>No extensive similarity was found with the regulatory proteins AraC , RhaC , MelR , ArgR , BioR or LysR from E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1851954" target="_blank">1851954</a>]<br></li>
<li>CRP is not needed for MelR-dependent repression of the melR promoter To investigate the possibility that the activator CRP is required for repression of the melR promoter by MelR , we constructed derivatives of the TB20 fragment carrying mutations that inactivated either or both DNA sites for CRP , and measured MelR-dependent repression ( Figure 5A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
