<li>TB23 TB23 TB22 TB22 MelR RNA-1 RESULTS MelR − + − + Measurement of melR promoter activity : repression by MelR The starting point of this work was the TB20 EcoRI -- HindIII fragment that covers the intergenic region between the divergent E. coli melR and melA genes and the translation start points .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>The activity of the melR promoter carried by each mutant KK81 fragment was then measured in vivo in the presence and absence of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>This fragment was cloned into pRW70 and melR promoter activity was measured in the absence and presence of pJW15 , encoding MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNA fragments ( 4 nM ) , containing the TB22 and TB28 derivatives of the melR promoter as indicated , were incubated with puriﬁed MelR as follows : lane a , no MelR ; lane b , 2000 nM ; lane c , 1000 nM ; lane d , 500 nM ; lane e , 250 nM and lane f , 125 nM .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Binding of Fe-BABE-labelled MelR to melR promoter DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
