<li>We show that the melR promoter is repressed by MelR and that this autoregulation requires MelR binding to Site R .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>First , in KK81S2 , the melAB 210 hexamer was altered from CATGAT to CGTGAT , a change that completely suppresses all melAB promoter activity ( S. Busby , unpublished data ) : this change has little or no effect on repression of the melR promoter by MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results argue that different conformational states of MelR are responsible for activation of the melAB promoter and repression of the melR promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Supporting evidence for this is provided by the isolation of substitutions in MelR that block melibiose-dependent activation of the melAB promoter while not changing melibiose-independent repression of the melR promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the melR promoter is not eficiently repressed by MelR , and MelR is over-expressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>The melR promoter and its repression by MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that occupation of sites 1 and 10 by MelR plays a role in repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , we now argue for a repression complex rather than a repression loop , and , taken together , our results suggest that this complex involves MelR bound at sites 1 and 10 , as well as at site 2 and site R .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>We show that repression requires a complex involving four DNA-bound MelR molecules , and that the global CRP regulator plays little or no role .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>We show that the simple looping model is not applicable and that repression involves four bound MelR molecules , and we argue for a repression complex rather than a repression loop .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our principal conclusion is that optimal repression does require MelR binding at distant targets , but it is more complicated , involving four molecules of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>The simplest model is that repression is dependent on the formation of a complex involving more than one molecule of MelR and we have found that optimal repression requires the binding of MelR at sites R , 2 , 1 and 10 , but not the binding of CRP at its targets .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>With one exception , each of the different single MelR substitutions results in a small reduction in the MelR-depen-dent repression of pmelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The exception is the GS119 MelR substitution , which results in a much greater reduction in repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , MelR-dependent repression is enhanced by the 13G change which introduces a consensus G. To determine experimentally the orientation of MelR bound at site R we used complementary genetic and biochemical approaches .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , repression of the 5C derivative is reduced with Val273 MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>We considered that some of the mutations might be causing a subtle change in MelR that shifts its conformation towards the active form .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>M182 cells carrying this plasmid were grown in media carrying 35 , ug of tetracycline/ml : the cells are Lac - , as lacZ expression is controlled by pmelAB , which requires MelR for activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>The simplest explanation of our data is that melibiose switches MelR from a conformation that is unable to activate pmelAB to a conformation that is able to activate pmelAB and that the different MelR substitutions favor adoption of the latter conformation to different extents .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The substitutions in the MelR mutants described above appear to bias MelR towards a conformation that can activate pmelAB but is unable to repress pmelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The QR238 TA277 derivative was isolated as a spontaneous pJW15 mutant during screening for MelR mutants competent for melibiose-independent activation of pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , some melR alleles unable to activate pmelAB result in Lac colonies , and 50 such colonies were a The ﬁrst column of the table lists the substitutions in different MelR deriv-atives selected as competent for melibiose-independent activation of pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>These DNAs , which encode mutant MelR that is unable to repress pmelR , presumably due to a defect i a The ﬁrst column of the table lists the substitutions in different MelR deriv-atives selected as defective for melibiose-dependent activation of pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results are most easily interpreted by a two-state model for MelR in which one state is fully competent for activation of pmelAB but is unable to repress pmelR , and vice versa for the other state .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>We reasoned that the difference between the form of MelR unable to activate pmelAB but competent for repression of pmelR and the alternative form that can activate pmelAB but is unable to repress pmelR might be , in part , due to subunitsubunit interactions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , melibiose toggles MelR between a state where it represses pmelR and is unable to activate pmelAB to a state where pmelR is derepressed and pmelAB is activated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>This strong repression is relieved by melibiose and , thus , melibiose toggles MelR between two alternative states , one that activates pmelAB and one that represses pmelR ( Fig. 1B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Results in Table 7 show that wild-type MelR is unable to activate expression from the JK141 promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>We reasoned that col-onies exhibiting an enhanced Lac phenotype must carry pJW15 plasmids encoding MelR mutants ( designated MelR ) able to activate pmelAB in the absence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Plasmid pJW15 was used to supply MelR to activate expression of the pmelAB : : lac fusion carried by KK43-pRW50 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>When triggered by melibiose , wild-type MelR requires the assistance of CRP to activate transcription at pmelAB ( 31 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION Melibiose is needed for wild-type MelR to activate transcription initiation at pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR mutants that are less able to activate pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>This shows that MelR carrying these substitutions has a reduced requirement for CRP to activate pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In preliminary experiments in E.coli strain M182 , we failed to detect activation of pmelAB with any of the truncated MelR proteins , suggesting that even the shortest deletion of 82 residues at the N-terminus of the protein , suppressed the activation function ofMelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>In vifro binding of MeIR derivatives to pmelAB To test whether the truncated MelR proteins could recognise the MelR binding sites at pmelAB , gel retardation assays were performed in vitro , using crude extracts of E.coli M182 containing pCM1 18 derivatives encoding full-length or truncated MelR derivatives .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Secondly , none of the truncated MelR derivatives were competent to activate transcription pmelAB , suggesting that the at N-terminal region carries functions for activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in contrast to MelR , N-terminal deletions in AraC give truncated proteins competent for inducer-independent transcription activation ( 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>After screening 10000 colonies , we purified six independent pJW15 derivatives carrying simple substitutions in MelR that resulted in detectable activation of mutant pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , this second screening step identiﬁed 11 pJW15 derivatives encoding MelR that were still able to repress pmelR , despite being defective in the activation of pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Assays for activation and repression by mutant MelR derivatives .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since it is likely that MelR-MelR interactions are important for both activation of pmelAB and repression of pmelR , we suppose that that differences recorded in Table 5 are due to differences in these interactions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>With KK433 , cells score as Lac - because MelR binding and pmelAB activation are reduced .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Oligonucleotide primers Name Sequence RESULTS Melibiose-independent activation of pmelAB by MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , transversion of the CG base pair at -104 led to a moderate reduction in MelR-dependent activation , suggesting that this base pair might be directly or indirectly involved in MelR binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>We suggest that efficient transcription activation requires that the MelR subunit bound at site 20 be in a particular conformation and that this conformation is determined in part by the sequence of the DNA target to which it is bound .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR protein thus belongs to a family of transcription activators which may share common features with respect , for example , to DNA binding and mechanism of transcription activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hence , both domains of MelR are required for transcription activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>These findings have important implications with respect both to the DNA specificity of MelR and its mode of transcription activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>The requirement of cooperative binding of MelR at sites 2 and 2 ′ explains the trans-dominant negative effect of MelR173 at pmelAB , despite the inability of MelR173 to-bind to the critical site 2 ′ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>The fact that a poor binding site at -- 35 enhances transcription activation by MelR emphasises the importance of the cooperative interactions between MelR proteins at adjacent sites in pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION To better understand the molecular mechanisms of transcription activation at pmelAB , we have compared binding of the full-lengt MelR transcription activator , MelR303 , to that of its C-terminal domain , MelR173 , which does not activate transcription , using DNase I footprinting and EMSA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>To further examine the mode of transcription activation by MelR , in this study we have explored the binding of MelR173 to these additional sites and the effect of CRP and compared this to the binding of full-length MelR ( MelR303 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition to these interactions , cooperative binding of MelR with CRP also enhances transcription activation ( 20,21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , purified MelR retarded the labelled DNA fragments less than did equivalent amounts of MelR in the crude extract ; although it is possible that some helper factor is being purified away , it is more likely that some MelR DNA-binding activity is lost during the purification .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>To quantify the combined effects of the four base changes on MelR binding , the KK43 , KK431 , KK432 and KK433 EcoRIHindIII fragments were purified and labelled and the binding o purified MeIR was measured by gel binding assays .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>According to these assays , our preparations of MelR were 70-80 % active in binding to the operator , and this was taken into account in calculating binding strengths for the different sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Intensities were measured in footprints obtained at different MelR concentrations , and lane-to-lane variation was accounted for by normalization to the intensities of bands at positions -35 and -65 , that are unaffected by MelR binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , we deduce that N222 , S271 and R273 in MelR and basepairs at positions 3 , 5 , 6 , 12 , 13 and 14 contribute to MelR binding to its target ( Fig. 8B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , and in full agreement with the previous results of Wade et al. ( 17 ) , the longer deletion in the TB23 fragment , that removes MelR binding site 2 , results in a sharp reduction in the repression of the melR promoter by MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this situation , MelR autoregulates its own expression by binding to site R and repressing its own promoter , and this repression is reinforced by upstream binding of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Weaker repression is due to residual binding of MelR to site R ( dotted outline ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>This shows that MelR can bind to site 1 without binding to site 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggested that the increased melAB expression in the W3133-2 mutant could be due to better binding of MelR to site 29 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>As the 48 mutants tested included base changes at all the 18 positions of MelR binding site 2 , we conclude that no single base is essential for MelR binding ( at least in the presence of multicopy melR provided by pJW15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indeed , the effects of the five base changes are greater with the JK14 fragment : this appears to be because MelR binding to site 29 is aided by MelR binding to sites 19 and 1 , and thus , in the absence of sites 1 and 19 , improvement of site 29 has a proportionately greater effect .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hydroxyl radical footprinting was used to study the binding of puriﬁed MelR protein to the JK19 fragment .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the next experiments , we used AFM to visualize the binding of puriﬁed MelR to its targets in the TB22 promoter fragment , to attempt to establish whether DNA loop formation is a feature of the MelR binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>As the protein -- DNA interactions appear to be identical in both MelR173 and MelR303 , cooperativity of binding to the adjacent DNA sites is probably due to protein -- protein interactions involving the N-terminal domain of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>We show that the purified protein binds to sequences at pmelAB and we present evidence that the C-terminal portion of MelR protein carries the elements responsible for binding to DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>We have recently shown that binding of CRP and MelR are cooperative , involving protein -- protein contacts ( 21 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>To examine whether MelR that is frozen in the activating conformation has the same requirement for CRP , we constructed the JK141 promoter , which lacks MelR-binding sites 1 and 1 and the pmelAB DNA site for CRP ( Fig. 1 ) , and cloned the resulting fragment in pRW50 to give plasmid JK141-pRW50 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNase I footprint analysis of MelR and CRP binding to pmelAB DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this case , bands corresponding to multiply bound MelR are observed and the data are consistent with normal MelR binding to Site 2 and reduced binding to Site 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>In view of this , we turned to genetic epistasis to attempt to identify interactions between MelR and its DNA target .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data allow us to determine the position of MelR binding at its target and to identify the DNA face along which it is bound .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Analysis of DNA cleavage patterns caused by FeBABE covalently bound to MelR permits us to ﬁx the orientation of MelR with respect to its binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>We have no simple explanation for this surprising result , although it is possible that bound MelR can interact with sequences downstream from the PstI site ( Fig. 1C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>The shortening appears to be due to compaction of the DNA between bound MelR molecules rather than to looping .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>The images from left to right show naked DNA , and the proposed complexes of MelR bound at sites 2 , 1 and 10 , and MelR bound at all four DNA sites 2 , 1 , 10 and R .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>From changes in the pattern of DNA cleavage at the melAB promoter , resulting from the differences in the location of the FeBABE tag on MelR , we have determined the orientation of MelR when bound to its DNA target sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR is drawn as in Fig. 6C , and the proposed orientation of the DNA sites for MelR is shown by arrows .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>This ﬁnding is similar to previous ﬁndings with the AraC and MelR proteins in which the activator binds to its upstream half-site much more tightly than its downstream half-site ( 8 , 9 , 18 , 31 ) and in the absence of ligand forms a DNA loop that represses transcription ( 30 , 41 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17513476" target="_blank">17513476</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results conﬁrm that helix -- turn -- helix 2 of MelR binds to the downstream half of site R and hence MelR must bind in opposite orientations at site R and site 2 ( Figure 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>The orientation in which MelR binds to site 2 and site 2 cents has important consequences , as it deﬁnes the surfaces of MelR that can make contact with the RNA polymerase s subunit and CRP during transcription activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The orientation in which MelR binds to site 2 cents appears to be determined by MelR -- MelR interactions rather than by MelR -- DNA interactions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , for site 2 cents at least , the orientation in which MelR binds appears to be dictated by protein -- protein , rather than protein -- DNA , interactions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unexpectedly , unlike wild type MelR , MelR173 did not bind to phosphocellulose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>This shows that MelR183 and Me1R173 bind to pmelAB and suggests that the in vivo effects on MelR-dependent activation of pmelAB observed with MelR220 , MelR183 and MelR173 are due to competition between these proteins and the wild-type protein for the MelR sites on the operator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , CRP depends on direct protein -- protein interactions with MelR and CytR to-bind low-afﬁnity CRP sites in the melA and deoC promoters , respectively ( 58 -- 60 ) Figure 8 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17068078" target="_blank">17068078</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the araBAD and melAB promoters AraC and MelR bind to alternative sites in the absence of inducer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15066032" target="_blank">15066032</a>]<br></li>
<li>CRP requires cooperativity with MelR and CytR to-bind to low affinity sites in the melAB and deoCABD promoters , among others .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17068078" target="_blank">17068078</a>]<br></li>
<li>To show this directly we have determined the DNAase footprint of the KK43 fragment in the presence of increasing concentrations of purified MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Electromobility shift assays showed that , while MelR can bind to Site R in the starting KK81 fragment , MelR is unable to-bind to Site R in the KK81S1 mutant ( J. T. Wade , unpublished data ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>As expected , MelR is able to discriminate between different sugars : activation is optimal with melibiose , some activation is found with galactose and raffinose , but none is found with lactose , fucose , rhamnose , arabinose or sucrose ( a full study of the sugar specificity of MelR will be presented elsewhere ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , CRP can regulate transcription of other transcription factors , such as MelR , RpoH , BlgG , Fis and PdhR , which could further regulate transcription of genes involved in the above processes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15520470" target="_blank">15520470</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , we propose that four subunits of MelR and two subunits of CRP cooperate together to form a higher structure that is needed to-coerce MelR into Site 20 , which is crucial for activation ( illustrated schematically in Fig. 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>The apparent explanation for our observation is that CRP makes a direct interaction with MelR bound to Site 1 and Site 2 and this recruits the CRP dimer to the 20 bp gap between the two bound MelR subunits .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>This argues strongly that the role of MelR bound at Site 1 and Site 10 , and of CRP bound between Site 1 and Site 2 , is primarily to ensure occupancy of Site 20 by MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>With the JK19 fragment , the changes in Site 20 result in a promoter where the requirement for MelR bound at Site 1 and Site 10 , and for CRP bound between Site 1 and Site 2 , is short circuited .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Prior to DNAase I treatment , the labelled DNA was preincubated with melibiose , MelR , cAMP ± CRP and RNAP ( 200 nM ) as indicated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Incubations contained 0.75 mM labelled MelR , 75 nM CRP and 200 mM cyclic AMP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this complex , MelR binds to two pairs of DNA sites , sites 2 and 20 and sites 1 and 10 , and CRP binds between the two pairs of sites ( Figure 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , tandem-bound MelR recruits CRP to the MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , TB201 is a derivative of TB20 in which the DNA site for CRP located between MelR site 1 and site 2 ( CRP1 ) is inactivated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activation of both araBAD and melAB requires that the lowerafﬁnity promoter-proximal operator be occupied by AraC or MelR , which occurs in the presence of inducer and cAMP/CAP ( Schleif , 1996 ; Wade et al. , 2001 ; Grainger et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15066032" target="_blank">15066032</a>]<br></li>
<li>This simple experiment shows that transcription initiation at melAB is totally dependent on the presence of MelR and a sugar cofactor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>CRP activation at some promoters , such as melAB and araBAD , is dependent on the presence of an additional regulator ( MelR and AraC , respectively ) ( 33,25 ) that is only induced by a speciﬁc substrate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15520470" target="_blank">15520470</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , the third line of data shows an important control ; expression in every case is minimal in the absence of MelR and CRP alone is unable to activate the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>The first line of data shows expression from the melAB promoter in the presence of both MelR and CRP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>The second line of data shows that , in the absence of crp , MelR induces low levels of expression from the melAB promoter on the KK43 fragment ; expression is less than 10 % of that seen in the presence of CRP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>This strain expresses low background levels of b-galactosidase but , after transformation with pJW15 , encoding MelR , melibiose-dependent induction of b-galactosidase can be measured resulting from MelR-dependent activation of the melAB promoter carried by the JK22 fragment .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 7B illustrates the results of an experiment in which melibiose-dependent activation of the JK22 melAB promoter by wild-type MelR , or MelR carrying the different alanine substitutions , was compared .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Summary The Escherichia coli MelR protein is a melibiose-triggered transcription factor , belonging to the AraC family , that activates transcription initiation at the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Summary The Escherichia coli MelR protein is a transcription activator that , in the presence of melibiose , activates expression of the melAB operon by binding to four sites located just upstream of the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , a major aim of this work has been to revisit these problems ; we report that we have now successfully reconstituted transcription activation at the melAB promoter in vitro and that this activation is dependent on MelR and melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>In previous work , we showed that MelR is a melibiose-induced transcription activator , related to AraC , that is essential for melibiose-induced activation of the E. coli melAB promoter ( Webster et al. , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR activity is regulated by melibiose , which is required for activation of transcription initiation at the melAB promoter ( Webster et al. , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of the E. coli K-12 melAB genes , which encode products essential for melibiose metabolism , depends on transcription activation by MelR and CRP , and is triggered by melibiose ( 7,9 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR is essential for induction of the melAB operon that is responsible for melibiose metabolism .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the presence of melibiose , MelR also binds 0 to a fifth site ( Site 2 , centred at position 242.5 ) located immediately downstream of Site 2 , and overlapping the 235 region of the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the presence of melibiose , the melR promoter can still be partially repressed by MelR binding to the site that overlaps the transcript start and 210 region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of melibiose , MelR is unable to activate the melAB promoter but autoregulates its own expression by repressing the melR promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>< 1.5 fold increase in the amount of transcript initiating at the melAB promoter in the presence of MelR and melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>We propose that , with the wild-type melAB promoter , MelR binds to Site 1 , Site 10 and Site 2 , both in the absence and the presence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>We propose that , for optimal repression , MelR forms a loop between Site R and Site 2 , and that this loop is broken in the presence of melibiose when the melAB promoter is activated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of melibiose , the conformation of MelR bound at Site 20 is such that it is able to interact with RNAP and to promote transcription initiation at the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>The presence of melibiose triggers a conformational change in MelR such that the dimer now occupies Site 2 and Site 20 and activation of the melAB promoter ensues .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Future efforts will be directed to understanding the synergy between MelR and CRP , and how melibiose affects the MelR ± RNAP interaction at this promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNAase I footprinting of RNAP at the melAB promoter Figure 6 shows a footprinting experiment in which DNAase I was used to investigate the binding of RNAP to the KK81 fragment in the presence of either MelR or MelR and CRP ( with or without melibiose ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>We showed that , in vivo , the melAB promoter carried by the JK19 fragment is fully active , dependent on melibiose and MelR , but independent of CRP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>In conditions where CRP is active , but melibiose is absent , MelR is made and occupies binding sites 2 , 1 , 10 and site R , but it can not occupy site 20 and activate the melAB promoter , and hence the system is ` poised ' ( 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Strikingly , all induction is lost with the JK14 fragment , showing that MelR binding to Site 1 and Site 10 is essential for activation of the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Model for MelR and CRP binding during activation at the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>We suggest that the effects of CRP on the activity of the melAB promoter may be due to an increase in the melibiose-dependent occupation of binding Site 20 by MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , melibiose is required for MelR binding to Site 20 and hence for activation of the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>A truncated version of the meiR gene , encoding the C-terminal half of MelR , was also cloned into pJLA502 ; the protein product of this truncated gene binds to the melAB promoter but was not overproduced .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>The present observation that MelR specifically binds to nt sequences at the melAB promoter , provides a compelling indication that MelR intervenes directly at the level of melAB transcription initiation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>We therefore quantity a series of N-terminal deletions of the MelR gene and constructed tested their DNA-binding properties in vivo and in vitro to find a short fragment that was stably expressed and still bound specifically to the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>With the JK14 fragment , expression is low , although some melAB promoter activity is detected as MelR is overproduced .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>We suppose that this improvement in MelR binding is responsible for the increased melAB promoter activity in the W3133-2 mutant , although we can not prove that it is solely responsible .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Taken together , our results show that the activity of the melAB promoter is limited by the binding of MelR to site 29 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the pmelR promoter , MelR binds at site R , centred just downstream of the transcription start point , and represses its own transcription ( 19 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Recent studies ( 11 ) have shown that the occupation of site 29 by MelR is the most crucial for the activation of the melAB promoter , but that , of the four target sites , site 29 binds MelR most weakly .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Additionally , although CRP is unable to-bind to the melAB promoter in the absence of MelR , in the presence of MelR , it binds to a site located between MelR binding Received 19 November , 1999 ; revised 21 January , 2000 ; accepted 24 January , 2000 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , at the melAB promoter , CRP binds between two MelR subunits and binding appears to be contingent upon the presence of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although there are very few known examples of E. coli proteins binding to noncanonical DNA sites , CRP binds to a noncanonical site in the melAB promoter in cooperation with MelR bound to adjacent DNA sites ( Wade et al. 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16264194" target="_blank">16264194</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to simplify our analysis , we exploited an engineered derivative of the melAB promoter in which MelR binding to site 2 and site 2 cents , in the absence of CRP , is sufﬁcient for transcription activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , at the E. coli melAB promoter , CRP binds to DNA cooperatively with the second activator , MelR , to increase MelR binding to the site that is required for transcription activation ( 4 , 33 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16166533" target="_blank">16166533</a>]<br></li>
<li>One possibility was that CRP binds to DNA cooperatively with RhaR to improv the ability of RhaR to activate transcription , similar to the cooperative binding of MelR and CRP at the melAB promoter ( 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16166533" target="_blank">16166533</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the NS50 , IT95 , MT243 , and SR271 substitutions result in noninducible ( NI ) MelR , we conclude that these changes lock MelR in the minus-melibiose conformation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In accord with this , we identiﬁed four NI mutants of MelR , NS50 , IT95 , MT243 , and SR271 , which appear to lock MelR in the minus-melibiose conformation and are fully competent for repression of pmelR ( Table 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>It remains to be seen whether the MelR mechanism involves the transmission of structural changes from its NTD to its CTD in the presence of melibiose in addition to releasing its DNA loop .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR is somewhat of a special case , however , given that in the absence of melibiose , MelR has been proposed to form a DNA loop that actively represses melR transcription ( Wade et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our in vitro studies have shown that MelR alone binds to site 1 cents , site 1 and site 2 , but that occupation of site 2 cents , which is essential for transcription activation , requires the presence of melibiose and CRP ( Williams et al. , 1994 ; Belyaeva et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our in vitro studies , showed that MelR can bind to this site in both the presence and absence of melibiose , that this site accommodates just one MelR subunit , and that binding is tightened by CRP ( Belyaeva et al. , 2000 ; T. A. Belyaeva , unpublished data ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the accompanying paper ( Belyaeva et al. , 2000 ) , we showed that Site 2 is occupied by MelR in both the absence and presence of melibiose whereas the neighbouring Site 20 is only occupied by MelR in the presence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , both the MelR and AraC proteins bind to their cognate sites in both the presence and the absence of the cognate activator ( arabinose and melibiose respectively ) ( Webster et al. , 1989 ; Lobell & Schleif , 1991 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>( B ) Interactions of MelR with the different sites in the absence and presence of melibiose as proposed by Wade et al. ( 30 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , because high levels of induction are found only with the JK19 insert , we conclude that a site resembling Site 10 rather than Site 1 is necessary for MelR and/or the target DNA to adopt the correct conformation for activation ; the binding of melibiose may induce this conformation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>It has been proposed ( 30 ) that repression requires the formation of a DNA loop that is stabilized by MelR binding at site R and site 2 and that the presence of melibiose breaks this loop , resulting in derepression of pmelR , occupation of site 2 , and induction of pmelAB ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , Fig. 4 lanes d and e show that , in the presence of MelR , CRP affords clear protection of the DNA between MelR binding Site 1 and Site 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , in the presence of melibiose , the recruitment of CRP results in increased protection of MelR binding site 20 ( Fig. 4 , compare lanes e and h ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , even in the presence of melibiose and higher concentrations of MelR , very poor protection of the segment of DNA corresponding to MelR binding site 29 is observed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Finally , close examination of the DNAase I footprinting results indicates that MelR also protects < 20 bp far upstream near position 2240 , and that this protection is found both in the absence and the presence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>The open triangle denotes Site 20 that is filled by MelR only in the presence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>The presence of melibiose induces a conformation change in MelR such that it is able to occupy Site 20 : this requires a complex of at least four MelR subunits and one CRP dimer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since repression is greatly reduced by melibiose , we investigated whether it is reduced by the different MelR substitutions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the presence of melibiose , the degree of repression by MelR is similar with the long KK81 and the short KK101 fragments .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Surprisingly , the binding of MelR to target sites is unaffected by the presence or absence of melibiose : whilst all the experiments presented here were performed in the presence of melibiose , there were no differences when melibiose was omitted or if the extracts were extensively dialysed to remove possible low-M , inducer molecules ( C.W. , unpublished ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of MelR and melibiose , purified RNAP induces clear reactivity of bases around position 210 upstream of the melAB transcript start site ( Fig. 3 , lane h ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>In our previous work ( 30 ) , we showed that , in the absence of melibiose , the expression of a pmelR : : lac fusion could be repressed 10-fold by MelR and that this repression required MelR binding to site R , overlapping pmelR , and to site 2 , located 176 bp upstream .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of melibiose , MelR occupies the other four sites , and this results in repression of pmelR ( 30 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the absence of melibiose , MelR still binds at site 2 and at site R , and this results in strong repression of pmelR ( 30 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of melibiose , MelR is unable to occupy site 2 , and an interaction between MelR bound at site 2 and site R causes strong repression of pmelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the presence of melibiose , MelR occupies site 2 , the interaction between site 2 and site R is broken , and the strong repression of pmelR is relieved .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of melibiose , greater repression occurs in the presence of MelR binding Site 2 , located 177 bp upstream .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of melibiose , we propose that a MelR dimer simultaneously occupies Site R and Site 2 , creating a repression loop .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>This may be a mechanism to ensure that MelR is unable to-bind to site 2 cents in the ` correct ' orientation , to activate transcription , in the absence of its inducer , melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of melibiose , MelR and CRP bind to form a complex , but site 2 is not occupied .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutant MelR that is active in the absence of melibiose has less need for CRP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>This complex can not form in the absence of melibiose because MelR , whilst binding to sites 2 , 1 and 10 , is unable to occupy site 20 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of melibiose , we found very little evidence for binding of MelR to this site ( Fig. 4 , compare lanes g and i ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>First , we studied the binding of MelR in the absence of melibiose ( see Fig. 4 , lane g ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Purified KK81 fragment was end-labelled at the HindIII site and treated with permanganate after preincubation with different combinations of purified RNAP , cAMP-CRP , and MelR , in the presence or absence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR can occupy this site in both the presence and absence of melibiose , and this appears to provide the cell with a fairly simple autoregulatory mechanism to ensure that MelR protein is never overexpressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR can bind to Site 1 , Site 1 , Site 2 and Site R , in both the absence and the presence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR binds to site 2 only in the presence of melibiose ( 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The other mutants contain substitutions throughout the central part of MelR and appear to alter the conformation of MelR , such that activity is triggered at lower melibiose concentrations and by arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>The most surprising result from this work was the identification of a set of substitutions at disparate positions in the central portion of MelR that increase the sensitivity ofMelR to activation by melibiose and arabinose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>The inducer for AraC is arabinose and for MelR , melibiose but both these sugars are taken up by permeases producing free sugar in the cell .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15066032" target="_blank">15066032</a>]<br></li>
<li>The simplest explanation for the effects of these changes is that they alter the conformation of MelR to-bind more tightly to melibiose and to relax the specificity of inducer binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>The aim of this work was to exploit mutational analysis to understand how melibiose binding modulates the activity of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In preliminary experiments , we targeted mutations to the segment of melR encoding the 20 N-terminal amino acids of MelR , but we were unable to ﬁnd any changes that resulted in MelR capable of melibiose-independent activation of pmelAB ( T. A. Belyaeva , unpublished data ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Surprisingly , none of our mutant MelR derivatives had lost the requirement for melibiose to trigger induction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Substitutions in different parts of MelR must be combined to create fully active melibiose-independent MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>This activation is dependent on MelR and melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since the activity of MelR in vivo can be triggered by melibiose , we measured the concentration-dependence of melibiose activation for the different MelR mutants .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , melibiose must trigger a conformational change in MelR required for activation , independent of any change in binding affinity or preferences .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is because activation requires MelR binding to site 2 that overlaps the pmelAB 35 hexamer element , and melibiose is required for wild-type MelR to occupy this site ( 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this regard it is worth noting that , although MelR-dependent stimulation of gene expression in vivo is dependent on the addition of melibiose to the medium , the binding of purified MelR at pmelAB is not dependent on melibiose in vitro ( Webster et al. , 1989 ; Caswell et al. , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR activity can be triggered by the inclusion ofmelibiose in the growth medium ; the role of MelR is activate to transcription initiation at the melAB ( pmelAB ) in promoter response to melibiose or , possibly , some other metabolite .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription from pmelAB is totally dependent on MelR and the presence of melibiose in the medium ( 2 ) , while transcription from pmelR depends on the global transcription activator , the cyclic AMP receptor protein ( CRP ) ( 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , transcription initiation from pmelAB is totally dependent on the presence of melibiose in the growth medium , most likely because MelR activity is triggered by melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>We showed that expression from pmelAB is dependent on MelR and is triggered by the presence of melibiose in the growth medium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809031" target="_blank">8809031</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR activates expression of the melA and melB genes , encoding an α-galactosidase and a melibiose permease , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results in Table 2 show that , in the absence of melibiose , none of the MelR derivatives have any effect on expression fro pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Results in Table 3 show that , with each mutant MelR , the addition of melibiose increases the activity of pmelAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hence , with pJW15 carrying the double substitutions , pmelAB activity in the absence of melibiose ranges from 17 to 75 % of the activity with wild-type MelR in the presence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Further data listed in Table 3 show that , with pJW15 carrying these quadruple substitutions , pmelAB activity in the absence of melibiose rises to 90 % of the activity seen with wild-type MelR in the presence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Table 3 lists - galactosidase activity measurements , which showed that pmelAB activity is very low in the absence of melibiose and that melibiose triggers a 50-fold increase in pmelAB activity that is MelR dependent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Table 4 lists - galactosidase activity measurements , which conﬁrmed that , in the absence of melibiose , pmelR activity is repressed 10-fold by wild-type MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Titrations with melibiose revealed that the concentration of melibiose required for 50 % induction is increased by ﬁve - to eightfold compared to wild-type MelR ( C. L. Webster , unpublished data ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In most cases , the observed expression is similar to that observed with wild-type MelR in the presence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Each of the data points shown describes expression in the presence of the inducer , melibiose , and 100 % is taken as the level of expression with wild-type MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>In each case , activation was triggered by the addition of melibiose to the growth medium , and activation levels were significantly higher than those with wild-type MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , with four of the mutants ( FL53 , PS81 , TA117 , and ND183 ) , melibiose induces pmelAB activity , but to a lesser level than with wild-type MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Data are organized in groups of three to compare the effects of the three MelR substitutions , which are indicated by the shading of each bar .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Note that this induction is dependent on MelR , because no induction is found in the WAM132 DmelR strain ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although we have no structural data for MelR , its domain organization appears to be similar to AraC ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>This corresponds to the situation in the footprint experiment in Figure 1 ( b ) , where MelR binds more tightly to Site 2 than to Site 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>A puzzling aspect of this system concerns the location of the aa sequence in MelR that binds to the operator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>In each case the concentration of total protein was adjusted so that the total amount of MelR was constant .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expressed MelR protein was found to be in inclusion bodies , which were recovered by centrifugation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription initiation from PmelAB is stimulated by the MelR regulator with melibi-ose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>The different changes , listed in Table 5 , are distributed throughout MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The co-ordinates refer to locations in MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR binds to lates its own expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interactions between MelR subunits measured by BACTH .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
