				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>Thus , we selected pJW15 deriv-atives encoding MelR with the NA222 , QA229 and RA230 substitutions in HTH 1 and the SA271 , RA273 and SA276 substitutions in HTH 2 ( guided by the alignments shown in Fig. 7A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the surfaces of MelR adjacent to the C-terminally located HTH 2 are likely to be involved in any contact with the RNA polymerase s subunit , whereas surfaces adjacent to HTH 1 are placed so that they could interact with CRP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Presumably , in one state but not the other , the MelR-MelR interaction results in a productive interaction between the T18 and T25 adenylate cyclase fragments .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In each case , the linker sequence is bracketed and the position of the last MelR residue is numbered .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data are consistent with a model in which helix -- turn -- helix 2 of MelR contacts the downstream part of site R , with residue 273 interacting with the base pair at position 13 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Several unbiased searches for other interesting features in the MelR sequence have focused our attention to the C-terminal end of the protein ; the last 34 aa contain no acidic residues , seven basic residues , nine resi-dues containing a hydroxyl group , and five glutamines ( Fig. 5 , line 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>In preliminary experiments in E.coli strain M182 , we failed to detect activation of pmelAB with any of the truncated MelR proteins , suggesting that even the shortest deletion of 82 residues at the N-terminus of the protein , suppressed the activation function ofMelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since it is likely that MelR-MelR interactions are important for both activation of pmelAB and repression of pmelR , we suppose that that differences recorded in Table 5 are due to differences in these interactions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Note that , for clarity , different amino acid residues in MelR173 are referred to by their location in full-length MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The resulting fusions encode proteins with the GalE N-terminal four amino acids plus a seven amino acid linker , added to the N-terminus of the truncated MelR derivatives ( i.e. Met-Arg-Val-Leu-Val-Thr-Ala-Cys-Glu-Ala-Ala-MelR ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>The C-terminal region of MaoB ( amino acid residues 182 to 217 ) was 46.9 % identical over 32 amino acids to AraC of E. coli and 30.8 % identical over 39 amino acids to MelR of E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631685" target="_blank">8631685</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 7A shows the amino acid sequences of the likely recognition helices of the HTH motifs of MelR and other AraC-family members , aligned according to Gallegos et al. ( 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Starting with plasmid pJW15 , which carries the cloned melR gene , a series of derivatives was constructed , encoding mutant proteins in which each amino acid in the two putative recognition helices of MelR was replaced with alanine .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>As it appeared that the removal of one protein -- DNA contact failed to disrupt promoter activation , we reasoned that most of the amino acid side-chains in the DNA-recognition helices of MelR that make base-speciﬁc contacts are among those in which the alanine substitution produced small effects .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Each MelR subunit is drawn as an oval , representing the C-terminal module , joined to a square , representing the N-terminal module that carries the determinants for subunit -- subunit interactions ( Howard et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>In complementary experiments , we used genetic analysis to investigate the importance of different residues in the two HTH motifs of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>We chose derivatives carrying substitutions in MelR binding site 2 at basepairs that are predicted to be in the major groove on the DNA face to which the MelR HTH motifs bind ( deduced from hydroxyl radical footprinting : Fig. 6A ) as these are the basepairs likely to make direct contact with MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Boxes indicate the basepairs that are predicted to be in the major groove on the DNA face to which the MelR HTH motifs bind , deduced from hydroxyl radical footprinting ( Fig. 6A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data support a model ( Figs 3 and 8B ) in which N222 in HTH 1 contacts the basepairs at positions 5 and 6 of MelR binding site 2 ( i.e. the upstream end ) , and R273 in HTH 2 contacts the basepairs at positions 12 and 13 ( i.e. the downstream end ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>B. Sketch showing the suggested contacts of N222 in MelR HTH 1 and of R273 in MelR HTH 2 with different parts of MelR binding site 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 1A illustrates the KK39 EcoRI -- HindIII promoter MelR binding at the E. coli melAB promoter 337 Determination of the orientation of bound MelR using FeBABE : studies with MelR173 MelR contains two HTH DNA-binding motifs : HTH 1 ( which contains residue N222 ) and HTH 2 , adjacent to its C-terminus ( which contains residue R273 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results ﬁx the orientation of the two HTH motifs of MelR with respect to these binding targets .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Patterns of DNA cleavage after MelR binding were then used to determine the positions of the two HTH motifs at target sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is the expected pattern from the binding of two MelR subunits to the adjacent site 2 and site 2 cents sequences , with each subunit using its two HTH motifs to penetrate two neighbouring segments of the major groove on one face of the DNA target .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>In MelR protein these correspond to residues 210-229 ( helix-turn-helix 1 ) and 259-278 ( helix-turn-helix 2 ) , which are illustrated schematically in Fig. 7 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>To conﬁrm this , we used a preparation of puriﬁed MelR that had been labelled with an inorganic DNA cleavage reagent at residue 269 , adjacent to helix -- turn -- helix 2 ( 16 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>The MelR deriv-atives were puriﬁed , and the cysteine residues were tagged with p-bromoacetamidobenzyl-EDTA-Fe , an inorganic DNA cleavage reagent .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The DNA-recognition helices of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>In our work on structure/function studies previous MelR , we showed that the deletion of 16 or more amino acids from the of MelR abolished DNA-binding and , that MelR C-terminus activity was affected by substitutions in the putative helix-turn-helix regions ( 2,4,14,15 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Specific binding is unaltered by deletions that remove 1 or 6 amino acids ( aa ) from the C terminus of MelR , but is abolished by deletion of 16 , 24 or more aa residues .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>One of these mutants contained a substitution in a proposed helix-turn-helix region that most likely relaxes the sequence-specificity of MelR binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>First , we exploited the observation that the RV273 substitution in helix -- turn -- helix 2 , permits MelR to recognize binding targets with a T at position 13 ( 20 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutations in the C-terminal domain of MeiR Sequence comparisons show that MelR , and other members of the AraC class of proteins , contain two potential helix-turn-helix motifs in the C-terminal half of the sequence ( Henikoff et al. , 1989 ; Tobin & Schleif , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>The striking sequence similarities between MelR and other members of the AraC class of proteins provide circumstantial evidence that one or other of the two potential helix-turn-helix motifs in MelR may also be involved in binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>A number of amino acid substitutions were made in the recognition helices of two putative helix-turn-helix motifs in the C-terminal part of MelR , and the effects of these mutations on MelR-dependent transcription initiation at the melAB promoter have been measured .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results with amino acid substitutions in MelR are also consistent with the suggestion that helix-turn-helix 2 is involved in DNA-recognition .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>These are the first reported single amino acid changes in MeIR , and although their effects do not provide a direct proof that motif 2 is involved in DNA-binding , they do raise the possibility that MelR differs from AraC , in which changes in the helix-turn-helix corresponding to motif 1 have clearer effects than changes in the sequence corresponding to motif 2 ( Brunelle & Schleif , 1989 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>In another study ( 16 ) , it was found that base pairs 5 and 13 of the consensus sequence make important contacts with the side chains of amino acids N222 and R273 , respectively , in the ﬁrst and second helix -- turn -- helix motifs of the MelR DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>To attempt to confirm that the C-terminal part of MelR is involved in DNA-binding and to examine the role , if any , of these putative helix-turn-helix motifs , we used site-directed mutagenesis to create changes at key residues in these sequences .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>The members of this family are most homologous in their C-terminal regions where two DNA-binding helix-turn-helix structures have been predicted ( at positions 210-229 and 259-278 for MelR ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>We suppose that this improvement in MelR binding is responsible for the increased melAB promoter activity in the W3133-2 mutant , although we can not prove that it is solely responsible .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , after poly-in extracts made of proteins crude acrylamide gel analysis from heat-induced M182 cells carrying pRC10 , we found no evidence for overproduction of the C-terminal domain of MelR ( results not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>Secondly , none of the truncated MelR derivatives were competent to activate transcription pmelAB , suggesting that the at N-terminal region carries functions for activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Hence , both domains of MelR are required for transcription-activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effect of the rpoA341 mutation on pmelAB activity A previous report [ 10 ] has shown that the phs mutant , which creates a single amino acid substitution in the C-terminus of the RNA polymerase α subunit , results in cells displaying a Mel − phenotype , and has suggested that the C-terminal domain of the α subunit may be essential for transcription-activation by MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809031" target="_blank">8809031</a>]<br></li>
<li>The orientation in which MelR binds to site 2 and site 2 cents has important consequences , as it deﬁnes the surfaces of MelR that can make contact with the RNA polymerase s subunit and CRP during transcription-activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ﬁnal possibility is that MelR activates transcription by contacting the C-terminal domain of the RNA polymerase α subunit and that the sequence from ® 36 to ® 54 acts as a docking site for this domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809031" target="_blank">8809031</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription activation at the Escherichia coli melAB promoter : interactions of MelR with the C-terminal domain of the RNA polymerase alpha subunit .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15342598" target="_blank">15342598</a>]<br></li>
