Transcription activation at the Esherichia coli melAB promoter : interactions of MelR with its DNA target site and with domain 4 of the RNA-polymerase-sigma subunit .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22465792" target="_blank">22465792</a>]<br></label>
<input id="dom_similarity_49", type="checkbox">
<div class="DOM_similar">
<li>Transcription activation at the Escherichia coli melAB promoter : interactions of MelR with its DNA target site and with domain 4 of the RNA-polymerase-sigma subunit .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Figure 3 shows gel binding analyses of the binding of purified MelR to the four labelled fragments .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>This means that each site provides sufficient nucle-otides to guarantee the binding of both HTH motifs belonging to the C-terminal domain of each subunit in the functional dimer , as reported for other members of the AraC/XylS-family such as AdpA , AraC , MelR and XylS ( Reeder and Schleif , 1993 ; Gonzalez-Perez et al. , 1999 ; Grainger et al. , 2003 ; Yamazaki et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although we have no structural data for MelR , its domain organization appears to be similar to AraC ( Fig. 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among proteins in this subset , including RhaS and RhaR as well as XylS , MelR , and UreR , this domain is generally required for dimerization and/or effector-binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC/XylS-family proteins whose DNA-binding domains do not activate transcription well -- including MelR and ToxT ( Howard et al. , 2002 ; Prouty et al. , 2005 ) -- may be similar to RhaR and unable to effectively contact RNAP ( or otherwise activate transcription at a step after DNA-binding ) in the absence of effector ( Fig. 6C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conclusions Comparison of MelR with other proteins of the AraC/XylS-family , suggests that the C-terminal half consists of a domain that is involved in specific binding to the melAB promoter ( 5-7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that the interactions of the two proteins with DNA are similar and so require solely the C-terminal domain of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the binding of melibiose to the MelR N-terminal domain is required to transmit an activatory signal to the MelR C-terminal domain , and both the N - and C-terminal domains are required for activation of pmelAB expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our studies show that both domains of MelR are involved in cooperative interactions ; the C-terminal domain in interactions with CRP , while the N-terminal domain is required for interactions between MelR proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>The C-terminal domain of MelR ( MelR173 ) does not activate transcription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>DISCUSSION To better understand the molecular mechanisms of transcription-activation at pmelAB , we have compared binding of the full-lengt MelR transcription activator , MelR303 , to that of its C-terminal domain , MelR173 , which does not activate transcription , using DNase I footprinting and EMSA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , the corresponding C-terminal domain of MelR alone is unable to activate pmelAB ( 12 , 17 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>These heterologous contacts must occur with the C-terminal domain of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , we suppose that melibiose binding to the MelR cupin fold triggers a concerted series of conformation changes that affect the N-termi-nal domain , the C-terminal domain , and the connecting linker .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In particular , amino acid sequence similarities argue that MelR residues 25 to 100 constitute a ligand-binding cupin fold ( 5 , 6 ) and MelR residues 190 to 302 fold as an AraC-family DNA-binding domain ( 29 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR consists of a C-terminal DNA-binding domain of ª 100 amino acids and an N-terminal melibiose-sensing-domain that also contains the determinants for the interactions between MelR subunits bound at different sites ( Michán et al. , 1995 ; Bourgerie et al. , 1997 ; Howard et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR consists of an 170-amino-acid melibiosebinding N-terminal regulatory domain joined to an 110-ami-no-acid DNA-binding domain via an 20-amino-acid linker ( 17 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Like many other members of the AraC-family , MelR appears to consist of two domains : a < 100 amino acid C-terminal DNA-binding domain and a < 200 amino acids N-terminal melibiose-sensing-domain ( MichaÂn et al. , 1995 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Like many members of the AraC-XylS family , MelR consists of an N-terminal ligand-binding domain connected , via a ﬂexible linker , to an 100 amino acid C-terminal DNA-binding domain ( 12,13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>This shows that binding of MelR303 at sites 1 ′ and 2 ′ in KK98 and KK99 is due solely to the cooperativity of binding with the adjacent site 2 and that this cooperativity requires the N-terminal domain of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>As the protein -- DNA interactions appear to be identical in both MelR173 and MelR303 , cooperativity of binding to the adjacent DNA sites is probably due to protein -- protein interactions involving the N-terminal domain of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>A preliminary deletion analysis shows that the C terminus of MelR is essential for binding to DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is a truncated derivative that carries MelR sequence from P132 to the C-terminus and contains the DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Substitutions In MeIR that suppress mutations In pmeIAB Current evidence suggests that the DNA-binding determinants of MelR are located in the C-terminal domain ( Caswell et al. , 1992a ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , we tested this directly , making a series of MelR deletion derivatives , to investigate whether a stable C-terminal DNA-binding domain could be isolated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our analysis revealed that substitutions resulting in melibi-ose-independent activation of pmelAB fall at loci throughout MelR and do not cluster in its N-terminal or its DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , some of the substitutions on our MelR mutants fall in the linker that joins the N-terminal ligand-binding domain and the C-terminal DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>a Our results provide important evidence that the C-terminal -50 % of MelR does fold independently forming a DNA-binding domain .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 3 shows a model of the C-terminal DNA-binding domain of MelR interacting at an 18 bp target .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Molecular model of the MelR DNA-binding domain at its target .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Domain organization of the E. coli MelR protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
