			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">MelR evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>Regarding carbon metabolism , members of the family control the degradation of sugars such as arabinose ( AraC ) , cellobiose ( CelD ) , melibiose ( MelR and MsmR ) , rafﬁnose ( RafR and MsmR ) , rhamnose ( RhaR and RhaS ) , and xylose ( XylR ) ; certain amino acids such as valine ( MmsR ) , arginine ( AdiY ) , and ornithine ( OruR ) ; alcohols such as 1,2-propanediol ( PocR ) ; alkylbenzoates ( XylS ) ; p-hydroxyphenylacetic acid ( HpaA ) ; and herbicides such as S-ethyl dipropylthiocarbamate ( TchR ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR protein thus belongs to a family of transcription activators which may share common features with respect , for example , to DNA binding and mechanism of transcription activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR belongs to a family of related activators and , to date , more than 27 members of this family have been identiﬁed [ 19 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809031" target="_blank">8809031</a>]<br></li>
<li>Optimal expression of the melAB promoter requires Sites 10 , Site 1 , Site 2 and Site 20 ; CRP acts as a ` bridge ' between MelR bound at Sites 10 and 1 and at Sites 2 and 20 , increasing MelR is a melibiose-triggered transcription activator that belongs to the AraC family of transcription factors .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>© 2002 Oxford University Press DNA binding of the transcription activator protein MelR from Escherichia coli and its C-terminal domain Victoria J. Howard , Tamara A. Belyaeva , Stephen J. W. Busby and Eva I. Hyde * School of Biosciences , The University of Birmingham , Edgbaston , Birmingham B15 2TT , UK Received December 30 , 2001 ; Revised March 11 , 2002 ; Accepted April 19 , 2002 ABSTRACT MelR is an Escherichia coli transcription factor belonging to the AraC family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Summary The Escherichia coli MelR protein is a melibiose-triggered transcription factor , belonging to the AraC family , that activates transcription initiation at the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Esch-erichia coli MelR protein appears to be a typical member of this family ( 33 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>In our studies , we have focussed attention on the E. coli MelR protein , which is a member of the AraC family .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>The predicted molecular mass of ChbR ( 33 kDa ) is similar to that of AraC and other family members , such as RhaS and MelR , involved in sugar metabolism in bacteria .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15066032" target="_blank">15066032</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because this site overlaps the 235 hexamer of the melAB promoter , it appears that MelR , like AraC and many other members of the AraC family , may be a typical `` Class II '' transcription activator ( 17 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Note that our results are most easily explained by supposing that MelR , like many AraC family members , is functional as a dimer .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR , like many AraC family members , is insoluble at higher concentrations , and structural studies have proven impossible .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC/XylS family proteins whose DNA binding domains do not activate transcription well -- including MelR and ToxT ( Howard et al. , 2002 ; Prouty et al. , 2005 ) -- may be similar to RhaR and unable to effectively contact RNAP ( or otherwise activate transcription at a step after DNA binding ) in the absence of effector ( Fig. 6C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18366439" target="_blank">18366439</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conclusions Comparison of MelR with other proteins of the AraC/XylS family , suggests that the C-terminal half consists of a domain that is involved in specific binding to the melAB promoter ( 5-7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>This DNA-binding domain has also been shown to be involved in transcription activation in a number of AraC/XylS family proteins including Ada , RhaS , AraC , MelR , MarA , SoxS , XylS , and UreR ( 1 , 4 , 5 , 15 , 16 , 20 -- 22 , 37 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15342598" target="_blank">15342598</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR is a member of the AraC family of transcription factors and binds to 18-base pair target sequences ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR is a member of the AraC family of transcription activators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR belongs to the AraC/XylS family of prokaryote transcription regulators that includes at least 30 other proteins , most of them activators ( 5-7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conclusions MelR is a member of the AraC/XylS family of transcription regulators , a group of at least 27 proteins that , with two exceptions , are all transcription activators .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is consistent with the results of recent molecular genetic studie of MelR ( 14,15 ) and other members of the AraC/XylS family ( 10,12,27-29 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>AraC family regulators that have been well characterized include AraC , MelR , XylS , RhaR , and RhaS ( 9 , 12 -- 18 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24013633" target="_blank">24013633</a>]<br></li>
<li>This group includes AraC , RhaS , RhaR , and MelR from E. coli and XylS from Pseudomonas putida , which are among the most well characterized of the AraC/XylS family proteins ( 4 , 5 , 8 , 12 , 13 , 16 , 19 , 29 , 30 , 38 , 39 , 53 -- 55 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10940041" target="_blank">10940041</a>]<br></li>
<li>The C-terminal region of MaoB ( amino acid residues 182 to 217 ) was 46.9 % identical over 32 amino acids to AraC of E. coli and 30.8 % identical over 39 amino acids to MelR of E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631685" target="_blank">8631685</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the amino acid sequence deduced from a new open reading frame ( maoB ) containing the element necessary for increased monoamine oxidase activity , we found high homology between the C-terminal region of MaoB and the conserved sequences in the C-terminal regions of members of the AraC family ( AraC , MelR , and RhaR , etc. ) , positive transcriptional factors ( 5 , 11 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8631685" target="_blank">8631685</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutations in the C-terminal domain of MeiR Sequence comparisons show that MelR , and other members of the AraC class of proteins , contain two potential helix-turn-helix motifs in the C-terminal half of the sequence ( Henikoff et al. , 1989 ; Tobin & Schleif , 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>The members of this family are most homologous in their C-terminal regions where two DNA-binding helix-turn-helix structures have been predicted ( at positions 210-229 and 259-278 for MelR ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>This means that each site provides sufficient nucle-otides to guarantee the binding of both HTH motifs belonging to the C-terminal domain of each subunit in the functional dimer , as reported for other members of the AraC/XylS family such as AdpA , AraC , MelR and XylS ( Reeder and Schleif , 1993 ; Gonzalez-Perez et al. , 1999 ; Grainger et al. , 2003 ; Yamazaki et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 7A shows the amino acid sequences of the likely recognition helices of the HTH motifs of MelR and other AraC family members , aligned according to Gallegos et al. ( 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>In particular , amino acid sequence similarities argue that MelR residues 25 to 100 constitute a ligand-binding cupin fold ( 5 , 6 ) and MelR residues 190 to 302 fold as an AraC family DNA-binding domain ( 29 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Like many other members of the AraC family , MelR appears to consist of two domains : a < 100 amino acid C-terminal DNA-binding domain and a < 200 amino acids N-terminal melibiose-sensing domain ( MichaÂn et al. , 1995 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Like many members of the AraC-XylS family , MelR consists of an N-terminal ligand-binding domain connected , via a ﬂexible linker , to an 100 amino acid C-terminal DNA-binding domain ( 12,13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
