				<div class="SIT"><br><ul><li>In pRClO , MelR sequence from Leu-159 to the Cterminal Gly-302 is attached to the N-terminal sequence Met-Asp-Ile-Ala-Gly , which is controlled by the atpE translation start and the A PL and PR promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>A puzzling aspect of this system concerns the location of the aa sequence in MelR that binds to the operator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , we decided to investigate the in vivo consequences of altering the base sequence of Site 20 to improve binding of MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because we already knew that MelR can bind tightly to Site 1 and to Site 10 , we replaced the base sequence of Site 20 in the JK14 fragment with that of either Site 10 ( JK19 ) or Site 1 ( JK20 ) ( see Fig. 7 and Experimental procedures ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Site 2 overlaps the 35 element of pmelAB , and MelR bound at site 2 activates transcription by making a direct contact with the RNA polymerase subunit ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The apparent explanation for our observation is that CRP makes a direct interaction with MelR bound to Site 1 and Site 2 and this recruits the CRP dimer to the 20 bp gap between the two bound MelR subunits .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>This argues strongly that the role of MelR bound at Site 1 and Site 10 , and of CRP bound between Site 1 and Site 2 , is primarily to ensure occupancy of Site 20 by MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>With the JK19 fragment , the changes in Site 20 result in a promoter where the requirement for MelR bound at Site 1 and Site 10 , and for CRP bound between Site 1 and Site 2 , is short circuited .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>To investigate whether MelR173 was binding to the same sequences at pmelAB as full length MelR , DNAase I footprinting assays were performed , using the KK43 EcoRI-HindlIl fragment carrying both MelR-binding sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>DNAase I footprinting shows that MelR173 and full-length MelR occupy the same two sites at pmelAB , although the shortened MelR derivative binds with -40 - fold lesser affmiity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
