<li>melA melR melB I # + + MelR MelB MelA B. pmelAB -113 site 1 49 ATTTATTCCCATAAACTCAGATTTACTGCTGCTTCACGCAGGATCTGAGTTTATGGGAATGCTCA TAAATAAGGGTATTTGAGTCTAAATGACGACGAAGTGCGTCC3GACTCAAATACCCTTACGAGT fte 2 Figure 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>The results conﬁrm that helix -- turn -- helix 2 of MelR binds to the downstream half of site R and hence MelR must bind in opposite orientations at site R and site 2 ( Figure 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>First , published band shift assays strongly suggest that two MelR subunits bind to the DNA sequence around Site 1 ( Bourgerie et al. , 1997 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Second , hydroxyl radical footprinting shows that MelR bound to Site 2 protects three sets of bases , each separated by 10 bp , consistent with the binding of a single MelR subunit penetrating two adjacent major grooves at its DNA target ( as for MarA ; see Rhee et al. , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>We attribute these bands to progressive occupation of the four DNA sites for MelR : as expected , the fourth , most retarded band remained quite weak , in agreement with our previous observation that MelR binds weakly to site 29 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>We show that the purified protein binds to sequences at pmelAB and we present evidence that the C-terminal portion of MelR protein carries the elements responsible for binding to DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=1445207" target="_blank">1445207</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results show that pmelAB sequences downstream of ® 51 have little or no activity , that MelR binding to the downstream site 2 is suficient for some ( but not for optimal ) melibiose-triggered expression , and that sequences upstream of site 1 contribute to pmelAB activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809031" target="_blank">8809031</a>]<br></li>
<li>These data support a model ( Figs 3 and 8B ) in which N222 in HTH 1 contacts the basepairs at positions 5 and 6 of MelR binding site 2 ( i.e. the upstream end ) , and R273 in HTH 2 contacts the basepairs at positions 12 and 13 ( i.e. the downstream end ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The images from left to right show naked DNA , and the proposed complexes of MelR bound at sites 2 , 1 and 10 , and MelR bound at all four DNA sites 2 , 1 , 10 and R .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>The binding of MelR to these sites in the KK98 and KK99 DNA fragments must therefore be due primarily to cooperative binding with MelR303 bound at the adjacent consensus sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>The locations of the different DNA sites for MelR are indicated by triangles : each triangle indicates an 18 bp sequence and the position of the centre of each site is numbered ( see Belyaeva et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>The locations of the DNA sites for MelR are indicated by shaded boxes : each box indicates an 18 bp site , and the position of the centre of each site is denoted.The black shaded boxes indicate the identical consensus site 1 and site 2 base sequences .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The locations of the DNA sites for MelR are indicated by horizontal triangles : each triangle indicates an 18 bp sequence and its orientation , and the position of the centre of each site is denoted ( these sequences are listed in Fig. 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>The locations of the DNA sites for MelR are indicated by triangles : each triangle indicates an 18-base pair sequence and its orientation , and the position of the center of each site is denoted .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>The upstream DNA binding site for MelR in the KK98 , KK99 and KK100 fragments , site 2 , was amplified as an EcoRI -- NsiI fragment using the following primers with KK43 as template : Upstream : 5 ′ - GCAGAATTCCCGGGGATCTGAGTTTAT Downstream : 5 ′ - GCAAAGCTTATGCATTCCCATAAACTCAG NsiI Site 2 This corresponds to the sequence -- 73 to -- 51 of pmelAB between two linkers .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Construction of KK98 , KK99 , KK100 and VH101 A series of DNA fragments were constructed containing site 2 of pmelAB and a second DNA binding site for MelR , increasingly like site 2 , in an 18 -- 2 -- 18 bp arrangement ( Figs 1 and 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>This fragment was inserted between the EcoRI and NsiI sites flanking the downstream half-sites to give KK98 , KK99 and KK100 , containing two DNA binding sites for MelR organised in an 18 -- 2 -- 18 bp inverted-repeat with a central NsiI site The VH101 DNA was constructed by replacing the EcoRI -- NsiI fragment in KK98 with two complementary oligonucleotides containing the sequence of site 1 ′ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Scrutiny of the DNA sequence just upstream of Site 1 reveals a possible further DNA site for MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>This 18 bp sequence ( which we call Site 10 ) is centred at position 2120.5 and corresponds to the Site 1 and Site 2 sequences at 12 of the 18 bases that this region carries a DNA site for MelR ; the DNA sequence reveals an 18 bp sequence centred at position 2238.5 , that corresponds to the Site 1 and Site 2 sequences at 11 of the 18 bases ( Fig. 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Ratio of Activity + MelR / -- Mel Optimal MelR-dependent repression of the melR promoter depends on upstream sequences 1 Transcription initiation of the melR promoter is dependent on the binding of CRP to a 22 bp DNA site centered at position 241.5 , but sequences further upstream are not essential ( Webster et al. , 1988 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>We previously identiﬁed two 18 bp consensus binding targets for MelR , site 1 and site 2 ( Williams et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Orientation of MelR bound at site R Wade et al. ( 17 ) showed that MelR-binding site R is essential for MelR-dependent repression of the melR promoter , and Figure 3A shows the proposed 18-bp binding sequence compared to the consensus ( 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>( A ) The ﬁgure shows an alignment of the consensus 18-bp DNA site for MelR , found at site 1 and site 2 , with the proposed sequence of MelR-binding site R at the melR promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18346968" target="_blank">18346968</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here , we show that MelR is a DNA-binding protein with a specific affinity for an 18-bp sequence that is repeated upstream from the meL4B tsp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 4 shows that the situation is radically different for MelR binding at pmelAB ; in this case , MelR binds clearly upstream of the ® 35 hexamer , with an 18 bp gap between the downstream MelR-binding site and position ® 35 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809031" target="_blank">8809031</a>]<br></li>
<li>The ﬁrst possibility is that the 18 bp of sequence upstream of the ® 35 hexamer comprises a third MelR-binding site and that MelR bound to this third site contacts the RNA polymerase σ subunit .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809031" target="_blank">8809031</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that the bases in site R that are the same as in site 2 but not conserved in site 1 ′ , i.e. A6 and G15 , are more important for binding MelR than those changed at site R , i.e. T8 , G13 and T18 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Analysis of DNA cleavage patterns caused by FeBABE covalently bound to MelR permits us to ﬁx the orientation of MelR with respect to its binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>We chose derivatives carrying substitutions in MelR binding site 2 at basepairs that are predicted to be in the major groove on the DNA face to which the MelR HTH motifs bind ( deduced from hydroxyl radical footprinting : Fig. 6A ) as these are the basepairs likely to make direct contact with MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is the expected pattern from the binding of two MelR subunits to the adjacent site 2 and site 2 cents sequences , with each subunit using its two HTH motifs to penetrate two neighbouring segments of the major groove on one face of the DNA target .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our data show that , at binding site 2 and site 2 cents , MelR subunits bind as direct repeats on the DNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>This shows that MelR can bind to site 1 without binding to site 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>This DNA segment includes MelR binding site 2 and site 2 cents , which are boxed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>We suggest that efficient transcription activation requires that the MelR subunit bound at site 20 be in a particular conformation and that this conformation is determined in part by the sequence of the DNA target to which it is bound .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>The current studies support our previous suggestion that transcription activation at pmelAB requires the binding of MelR to site 2 ′ , which overlaps the -- 35 sequence of the promoter ( 20 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our aim was to find point mutations in the MelR-binding sites that stopped MelR binding and prevented MelR-dependent transcription activation , with the goal of exploiting these mutations to set selection for up a substitutions in MelR that compensated for the changes in the binding site sequence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>We noted that the base changes in the melAB promoter in the W3133-2 mutant changed the DNA sequence of MelR binding site 29 such that it corresponded better to the tighter binding site 19 , site 1 , and site 2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Base sequence of different binding sites for MelR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>The base sequence of both strands of the DNA segments carrying the MelR binding sites at the JK19 melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>The requirement of cooperative binding of MelR at sites 2 and 2 ′ explains the trans-dominant negative effect of MelR173 at pmelAB , despite the inability of MelR173 to bind to the critical site 2 ′ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>aim study derivative that could recognise the DNA binding sites for MelR at pmelAB and could be stably overexpressed for further in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7784205" target="_blank">7784205</a>]<br></li>
<li>Patterns of DNA cleavage after MelR binding were then used to determine the positions of the two HTH motifs at target sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , it is likely that flanking sequences contribute to binding stability , and Caswell et al. ( 1992b ) argued that MelR binding to Site 1 but not Site 2 can be of upstream sequences .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the basis of identities in their base sequences , we had previously supposed that two MelR subunits bind to site 2 and site 2 cents ( and to site 1 and site 1 cents ) at the melAB promoter in an inverted orientation ( Belyaeva et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Also , we were puzzled that the binding sites for MelR at the melAB promoter were located further upstream than binding sites for other AraC family members at their target promoters ( Keen et al. , 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR-dependent activation of the melAB promoter requires the binding of MelR subunits to four 18 bp sites and the binding of a single CRP dimer to a low-afﬁnity target sequence ( Belyaeva et al. , 2000 ; Wade et al. , 2001 ; see Fig. 1A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although there are very few known examples of E. coli proteins binding to noncanonical DNA sites , CRP binds to a noncanonical site in the melAB promoter in cooperation with MelR bound to adjacent DNA sites ( Wade et al. 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16264194" target="_blank">16264194</a>]<br></li>
<li>Bounded by EcoRI site at 176 and HindIII site at 2272 ( with respect to melR transcript start ) Derivatives of KK81 carrying single base changes in MelR binding Site R ( see Fig. 3 ) Derivative of KK81 with Site R altered to : 50 TTCGTAGGAATATCAGAA 30 ( changes underlined ) Derivative of KK81 with 210 hexamer of melAB promoter changed from CATGAT to CGTGAT Derivative of KK81 with Site 1 altered to : 50 ATCGTAATAAACTCAGAT 30 ( changes underlined ) Derivative of KK81 with Site 10 altered to : 50 ATCGTATGAAAAGCAGAG 30 ( changes underlined ) Derivative of KK81 with Site 2 altered to : 50 ATCGTAATAAACTCAGAT 30 ( changes underlined ) Carries melR promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>The JK19 EcoRI -- HindIII fragment is illustrated in Fig. 1A , and the base sequences of MelR binding site 2 and site 2 cents are shown in Fig. 1B .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Repression of pmelR requires MelR binding to site R , which overlaps the melR promoter , but also MelR binding to site 2 , located 176 bp upstream .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>The TB20 pmelR fragment carries the melR promoter and upstream sequences , including MelR site 2 ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16621812" target="_blank">16621812</a>]<br></li>
<li>Using DNase I footprinting and gel retardation assays , we show that MelR binds to two sites located from nucleotides ( nt ) -49 to -75 and -85 to -113 , upstream from the melAB transcription start point .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutational analysis et at the upstream site ( Site 1 ) suggested that guanine position at a 104 with respect to the transcription start might be crucial for-MelR binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activation is dependent on the binding of MelR to four 18 bp sites , centred at position-42 .5 ( site 2 cents ) , position -62.5 ( site 2 ) , position -100.5 ( site 1 ) and position -120.5 ( site 1 cents ) relative to the melAB transcription start point .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 3 illustrates this arrangement , with basepair 1 of the DNA site for MelR shown corresponding to position -71 upstream of the melAB transcription start in the JK19 fragment , and basepair 18 corresponding to position -54 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR stimulates transcription initiation at the melAB promoter by binding to four sites centered at positions 2120.5 , 2100.5 , 262.5 , and 242.5 upstream of the transcript start point .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>At the melAB promoter , MelR binds to four such target sequences : site 19 , site 1 , site 2 , and site 29 centered at positions 2120.5 , 2100.5 , 262.5 , and 242.5 , respectively , upstream of the melAB transcript start point ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>Fulllength MelR ( MelR303 ) binds to two pairs of sites upstream of the melAB transcription start site , denoted sites 1 ′ and 1 and sites 2 and 2 ′ , and to a fifth site , R , which overlaps the divergent melR promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conclusions Transcription initiation at the melR promoter is downregulated by MelR , which binds to an operator site that overlaps the transcription start point and the 210 region .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of melibiose , greater repression occurs in the presence of MelR binding Site 2 , located 177 bp upstream .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Next , we made 4 bp changes at MelR binding Site 1 , Site 10 and Site 2 ( KK81S3 , S4 and 1 0.8 -- melibiose + melibiose 0.6 0.4 0.2 0 KK81 KK101 Fig. 4 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>In previous work , we have shown that MelR binds to two identical 18 bp sites upstream of pmelAB ( named sites 1 and 2 ) in both the presence and absence of melibiose ( 12,13 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12060687" target="_blank">12060687</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the case of pmelAB , transcription is dependent on MelR , which binds at two identical 18 bp sequences , organized as an inverted-repeat separated by 20 bp ( Figure 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>Conclusions Expression from pmelAB is completely dependent on the MelR protein , which binds to two 18 bp upstream elements organized as an inverted-repeat .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809031" target="_blank">8809031</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this work , we show that MelR additionally binds to 0 two other related 18 bp sequences : Site 1 , centred at position 2120.5 , located immediately upstream of Site 1 , and Site R , at position 2238.5 , which overlaps the transcription start site of the divergent melR pro-0 moter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>We previously described the overexpression and purification of MelR , and showed that MelR binds independently to two apparently identical 18 bp sites located at pmelAB , upstream of the transcription start site ( Caswell al. , 1992a , b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8010957" target="_blank">8010957</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the accompanying paper ( Belyaeva et al. , 2000 ) , we showed that , in the absence of melibiose , MelR binds to three 18 bp target sites ( Site 1 , Site 10 and Site 2 ) located just upstream of the melAB transcription start site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>We showed previously that MelR binds to two identical 18 bp target sequences centred at position 2100.5 ( Site 1 ) and position 262.5 ( Site 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Working with a short DNA fragment carrying the melAB promoter , we identified two identical 18 bp sequences centred at positions 262.5 and 2100.5 upstream from the melAB transcription start point and showed that these are binding sites for MelR in vitro ( Caswell et al. , 1992b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>In previous studies , using a shorter fragment , MelR binding to two identical 18 bp sequences centred at positions 2100.5 and 262.5 ( known as Site 1 and Site 2 respectively ) was detected ( Caswell et al. , 1992b ; Williams et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>Melibiose-dependent expression is suppressed by deletions that remove both DNA-binding sites for MelR and by point mutations in the ® 10 hexamer , the ® 35 hexamer and the INTRODUCTION The activity of most Escherichia coli promoters is dependent on ® ® two hexamer sequence elements , the 10 and 35 hexamers located around 10 and 35 bp respectively upstream from the transcript start point , that are recognized by the RNA polymerase σ subunit during transcription initiation [ 1 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=8809031" target="_blank">8809031</a>]<br></li>
<li>Upstream in the PmelAB promoter , two identical 18-bp elements are organized as an inverted-repeat from positions 2109 to 292 and from positions 254 to 271 ; these are the MelR binding sites ( 41 , 252 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9409145" target="_blank">9409145</a>]<br></li>
<li>The two MelR binding sites required for this optimal repression are separated by 177 bp .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760179" target="_blank">10760179</a>]<br></li>
<li>The present observation that MelR specifically binds to nt sequences at the melAB promoter , provides a compelling indication that MelR intervenes directly at the level of melAB transcription initiation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>MelR is a member of the AraC family of transcription factors and binds to 18-base pair target sequences ( 10 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10747919" target="_blank">10747919</a>]<br></li>
<li>We have no simple explanation for this surprising result , although it is possible that bound MelR can interact with sequences downstream from the PstI site ( Fig. 1C ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=2684786" target="_blank">2684786</a>]<br></li>
<li>Additionally , although CRP is unable to bind to the melAB promoter in the absence of MelR , in the presence of MelR , it binds to a site located between MelR binding Received 19 November , 1999 ; revised 21 January , 2000 ; accepted 24 January , 2000 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , in the presence of melibiose , MelR also binds 0 to a fifth site ( Site 2 , centred at position 242.5 ) located immediately downstream of Site 2 , and overlapping the 235 region of the melAB promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>We propose that , with the wild-type melAB promoter , MelR binds to Site 1 , Site 10 and Site 2 , both in the absence and the presence of melibiose .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10760178" target="_blank">10760178</a>]<br></li>
<li>For simplicity , Fig. 10 also shows MelR bound at site 1 and site 1 cents as a direct repeat ( in the opposite orientation to that at site 2 and site 2 cents ) , although this is a point that requires further experimentation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results show that MelR binds as a direct repeat to site 2 and site 2 cents with the C-terminal HTH located towards the promoter-proximal end of each site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>We can conclude that MelR occupies site 2 and site 2 cents at the wild-type melAB promoter as a direct repeat .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
<li>Figure 10 illustrates the likely organization of MelR subunits during transcription activation at the melAB promoter , with MelR binding to site 2 and site 2 cents as a direct repeat , in the same arrangement as for AraC at the ara-BAD promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12675795" target="_blank">12675795</a>]<br></li>
